\section{Search}

The results of a series of test runs are presented in the first part of this section, where the proposed intelligent active object search system and an uninformed system, which does not estimate likely object locations, are compared. In the second part of this section the behavior of the proposed system is evaluated in more detail based on individual runs. 

\subsection{Comparison between Intelligent and Uninformed Search}

\subsubsection{Settings}

The test runs were done using two different active object search systems. One is the proposed intelligent active object search system, which uses the gathered information about rooms, room types and object locations to speed up the search. The second one is a modified version of the proposed system, which does not use this additional information and is therefore called uninformed search system. Two changes were made to the proposed system to get the uninformed search system. Firstly, the detection of doorways is disabled, so the room structure is ignored. Secondly, every cell that can contain an object, which are cells within the room and not marked as free, have the same probability of containing the object. This is shown in Figure \ref{stupid_prob}. 
This results in a coverage maximizing search strategy because the objective function of the search planning in the uninformed system increases with the number of well seen cells in a view. 
\begin{figure}
\centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth, trim=0 30 0 80,clip]{figures/home_search/even_prob.png}
  \caption[Object probabilities in uninformed search]{Object probabilities in uninformed search: Red cells can contain the object and have the same low object probability}
  \label{stupid_prob}
\end{figure}

The test runs were done in the home environment. Eight different settings were chosen for the test runs, with four different searched objects and two different starting positions per object. Reliably detected objects were chosen to reduce the influence of the object detection and have more emphasis on the search planning. The objects were positioned in typical locations and a bit hidden, like in Figure \ref{hidden knife}, so they are not found during exploration and the robot has to search them. In Figure \ref{search_overview} the map of the environment is shown with marked room types, starting poses and object locations. In Table \ref{settings} the searched objects, their locations in the map and the starting poses are given for each setting. Also the areas, where, according to the used commonsense knowledge, the object is more likely, are stated. For each setting six search runs were done, three with the proposed intelligent search system and three with the uninformed search system, making a total of 48 runs. 

\begin{figure}
\centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth, trim=0 0 0 0,clip]{figures/home_search/knife.png}
  \caption{Image of the location of the knife searched in settings 5 and 6}
  \label{hidden knife}
\end{figure}

