\input{Evaluation/TimePlot.tex}
\input{Evaluation/LengthPlot.tex}

In the settings 1 and 2 the uninformed search system performed better than the intelligent search system. This has two reasons. On the one hand the intelligent search system decided in 4 of the 6 runs to search the room \textit{home2} first, so a lot of time was lost searching there. A more detailed description of the search behavior in these runs is given in the next section. In the other two cases, where the room \textit{home1} was searched first, the remote was found quickly. On the other hand the uninformed search system found the remote relatively quickly because the remote can be seen from a view pose, where the robot can cover a large area, which makes it a preferred view pose. Only once the remote was missed at the beginning, which, together with navigation problems, resulted in the one higher search time.

The search times in setting 3 highly depended on in which direction the exploration is done first. In Figure \ref{explore_split} can be seen that the exploration from starting pose 1 can go either first towards room \textit{home3} (image (a)) or towards room \textit{home2} (image (b)). Case (a) was found to happen about twice as often as case (b). In case (a) the intelligent search system first searches the room \textit{home3}, which costs some time, before the room \textit{home2} is discovered and the object is found. This problem of exploration vs exploitation is described in more detail in the next section. In case (b) the mouse is found quickly. On the other hand the uninformed search system performs better in case (a) because then the exploration ends near the searched mouse and the mouse is found quickly. This is shown in Figure \ref{mouse_uninf}.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{cc}
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/home_search/explore1.png}} &
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/home_search/explore2.png}}
\end{tabular}
\caption{Possible starts of the exploration from starting pose 1}
\label{explore_split}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth, trim=800 800 100 0, clip]{figures/home_search/stupid_fast_mouse.png}
\caption[Uninformed search of mouse]{Uninformed search of mouse: The trajectory during exploration (blue) and search (green) are show as well as the starting pose (cyan) and final pose, where object was found (purple)}
\label{mouse_uninf}
\end{figure}


The intelligent search system finds the object very quickly in setting 4 because the robot detects that it is already in a promising room, so only this room is explored and the mouse is found quickly. The uninformed search system is also relatively quickly in this setting as the mouse can be seen from a preferred view pose, where many cells are covered.

In the test settings 5, 6, 7 and 8 the intelligent search system performs much better than the uninformed search system. The uninformed search system needs more time in these settings because of the locations of the searched objects. The view poses, where those objects can be seen, cover not so many cells and therefore the uninformed search does only search there after some time. The intelligent search system always selects the correct room to search in these settings and most of the time the object is found quickly. In Figure \ref{spoons} the search trajectories for setting 7 and 8 of the intelligent search system are depicted.
\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth, trim=0 0 0 0, clip]{figures/example_runs/spoon.png}
\caption[Search trajectories for the intelligent search system in settings 7 and 8]{Search trajectories for the intelligent search system in settings 7 and 8: The trajectory during exploration (blue), move through doorway(red) and search (green) are show as well as the starting pose (cyan) and final pose, where object was found (purple)}
\label{spoons}
\end{figure}

The search trajectory lengths show slightly different results because switching high-level tasks and executing the peek tasks has no impact. Further the search trajectory lengths are not affected by navigation problems because there the robot does not move. The navigation problems have a big impact on the necessary time to search the room \textit{home2}, which consists mainly of narrow areas, as can be seen in the results of the intelligent search in setting 1. However, the trajectory lengths ignore the rotations of the robot, so the search time is still the better measurement for the search performance.

To wrap things up, the intelligent active object search system performs much better than the uninformed system except if multiple rooms are similar likely to contain the object. In this case a lot of time is lost by completely searching a room not containing the object. 

\subsection{Qualitative Evaluation of the Proposed System}

In Figure \ref{spoons} one can already see some examples how well the search within a room works. In the runs (b) and (f) the object is found in one of the first generated view poses, while in the runs (a), (c) and (d) the other side of the table was investigate first. This has to do with the position the search is started. In (b) and (f) the table is already seen a bit from one side, so the robot drives immediately to the other side of the table. In (d) the object was missed at the beginning, so a lot of the room was searched before the area with the searched spoon was investigated again. In Figure \ref{lab} a search for a bowl hidden in the kitchen area at the top left of room \textit{lab1} is depicted. The exploration takes most of the search time. After the exploitation the robot drives to some view poses in its vicinity and then immediately drives to the kitchen area and finds the object there.

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth, trim=0 0 0 100, clip]{figures/example_runs/lab_5.png}
\caption[Search for a bowl in the room \textit{lab1}]{Search for a bowl in the room \textit{lab1}: The bowl is hidden in the kitchen area in the top left corner. The trajectory during exploration (blue), move through doorway(red) and search (green) are show as well as the starting pose (cyan) and final pose, where object was found (purple) }
\label{lab}
\end{figure}

In Figure \ref{remotes} two search runs of setting 2 in the previous section are depicted. In the run shown in (a) the robot decided to search the room \textit{home2} first, while in the run shown in (b) the room \textit{home1} was searched first. In Table \ref{remote_tab} the object probabilities and expected search times are stated for both rooms and runs. In run (a) the room \textit{home1} is favored because the lower object probability in room \textit{home2} is offset by the much lower expected search time, which makes \textit{home2} the optimal next room to search.
\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{|l|c|c|}
\hline
run & (a) & (b)\\ \hline
object probability \textit{home1} & 0.213 & 0.249\\ \hline
expected search time \textit{home1} & 616\,s & 563\,s\\ \hline
object probability \textit{home2} & 0.158 & 0.153\\ \hline
expected search time \textit{home2} & 360\,s & 438\,s\\ \hline
\end{tabular}
\caption{Total object probabilities in room \textit{home1}}
\label{remote_tab}
\end{table}

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
